text: I'm actually really excited for this movie. I think it's disingenuous to say it look another Michael Bay film. It looks what even the first live-action film should'e been. The director Travis Knight worked as the lead animator for stop-motion animation studio Laika, and directed Kubo and the Two Strings (currently on Netflix). He also worked as an animator and producer on ParaNorman and Coraline. Those are quality films and until we actually see this movie he work shouldn't be spoken of in association with Michael Bay. At least in my opinion.

text: It looks fine and all but I still find it hard to get used to the fact, that this is a prequel. I mean the looks on the transformers are spot on, rocking the G1 designs, but in the Bay universe they are represented like moving and sliding pieces of garbage. Look at Shockwave for example. In this trailer he has the original Cybertronian look, but in the meantime in DotM he still has his so called alien look originated from his home planet. It feels a bit disconnected. It would have been good for this movie being a reboot. I hope we will see more of Cybertron, than we saw in this trailer. I don't want to get tricked by seeing it in the trailer and assume, that there will be more in the actual movie, whereas in reality the time it will be shown will be relatively short. We will see. I'm definitely going to see it. Cheers.

Like, I don't understand how Soundwave and Shockwave went from how they look here to how they look in the Bay films. Soundwave in particular doesn't look even remotely similar to his Bay design. Hell, even Cybertron looks different. Just put this movie in its own universe Paramount, I don't think anybody would be upset by that. But I guess this wouldn't be the first time continuity was thrown out the window...

text: I... Don't believe what I'm seeing. G1 designs that look respectable, a story that sounds genuinely promising that also hints to a kind of reboot, a director who actually has done a great film and apparently loves Transformers too... Could we finally, FINALLY have that live action Transformers Movie that is actually good, possibly great... perhaps even AMAZING!?  If Bay just produces it and ever ever directs it again and lets genuinely talented, artistic people take the director's chair and writing desk, then you bet I'll be for that!  EDIT: I just saw it.... I can't believe I'm saying this, but this movie wasn't just good, it was GREAT! I was laughing, I was invested, I CRIED AT ONE POINT! THIS is the Transformers movie we were waiting for! PLEASE let there be a sequel following THIS story line!

text: I like the emotions and how it focuses on characters far more than Bayformers... but those designs.. I am sorry, but Bayformers were atleast more fitting or could be taken a bit more serious in that "live action" layer.. I'd prefer the combination of designs that Bumblebee himself has achieved, he looks like a younger version of BayBee. And is pretty much instantly recognizible, but come on..  This is a movie, with a budget to do something pretty fresh and inovating to TF formula, but they just remake G1 TF movie, with cartoonish looks that couldn't work with the vision of our world. If they really wanted to go for G1 characters, they should have made it completly animated. Because it looks a bit silly to imagine Shockwave, Soundwave and all of those guys on Cybertron, in a cinematic that looks like from games, instead like a proper photorealistic movie style Bay has achieved, I mean, okay, Cybertron, but imagine those guys in front of humans. It just looks silly. I rather prefer a messy design, that looks like something that COULD actually stand right next to you and transform itself into a real car with all components inside, rather than a walking children tape recorder 15 meters tall.. But that is my own opinion.  Otherwise big respect to Travis Knight for a story that looks like a story, with emotions and really adorable main character.

In the cartoon, it was sped up, slowed down or stacked to match the visuals (Bumblebee is still making transforming sounds after he's in robot mode and even as he's flying through the air and hitting that ugly Bay-looking Decepticon) -it seems like we'll only get a glimpse of the aforementioned G1 goodness -military involvement  -Bumblebee's robot mode -Bumblebee still doesn't talk -John Cena  I hope the final trailer is better even though I know the designs that look bad won't change. ðŸ˜«

text: This is everything I've wanted from a live action Transformers movie since they first announced them back in the the mid 2000s.   This movie just NAILS the character designs.   THAT. IS. HUGE.   Especially for a series like Transformers where there are so many characters, color schemes and character design is everything. I'm so excited to see what they've got up their sleeve. Finally, we might have a story that is worthy of being just as loved as the War for Cybertron and Fall of Cybertron video games. I get the same kind of vibe with the Cybertron scenes here as I did while playing those games.   All in all, really REALLY excited for this movie. I'll have to see this one Day 1.   Best scene in the whole trailer for me was when Soundwave ejected Ravage. That just...my childhood!

text: So, a few things:  1) I wanna know who the old gentleman at the beginning is, because to me he seems to be the guy who you could just immediately like onscreen. 2) I love how the word 'deception' is emphasized into the Decepticon's characters in this one. Good wordplay. Gonna reeeeeeally hate those two... 3) Apparently Bee's melee weapon of choice is a serrated sheet rock knife. Neat. 4) I love the design of the Cybertronian jets-- it plays on how they looked in the first G1 episode. Good throwback. 5) G1 designs of the Cybertronian legends. These look so good...!! 6) A MUCH better Cybertron than how it looked in the Bay movies. Seriously... honeycombing is a bad idea. 7) Bee partially transforming to keep Charlie safe in his cab as he maneuvers out of the situation 8) The original transformation sound effects.  9) Bee being too gosh darn cute. Like seriously, gently brushing the sand out of Charlie's hair-- which, to put into perspective, is  giant metal hand the size of her *torso* that is gentle and tactile enough to not cause her harm. Also, the cute wave in the garage. Stahp, Bee. You too kyoot. 10) The poor guy's been forcefully attached to cables by humans enough times, guys, c'mon, leave him alone. Or else I will start kinkshaming you.

text: Okay guys, heres the deal.  Like if u think this movie is extremely good and unique compared to the other movies.  Now, why is it unique....First of all I get the "nostalgic vibe" of having the opportunity to see the real and original optimus and the other decepticons in their early and true forms. We get a good observation of cyberton. Moreover, just watching this trailer assures us that thier will be ups and downs with clear and proper climax moments unlike Bay's (yeah i know next goes baam baaam baam) bs. Previous films were good, but tbh yall have to agree that this movie has the qualities to change our mindset regarding the franchise.   Whats also good about this movie is that we get to see many transformers (which was also in the previous movies), but this time their is a straight objective of this movie and a clear goal for a main character transformer. No hassle no new york china bs.   The only thing i hope to see (might not happen) are the dino-bots. Thank u bay for lezving the franchise and kuddos to the new director.

text: Well, now we have both Blitzwing AND Starscream in the same film. I just hope we'll be able to tell the difference between the two once the film eventually comes out. But overall... this is it. This is the definitive live-action Transformers film we've been waiting for. The film we should've gotten in the first place before Michael Bay mucked it all up. The story actually has heart, the Transformer characters' personalities don't take a backseat to the humans', and the designs of the characters take SO much from their G1 designs (especially on those Cybertron scenes; I mean, just look at them!). Again, my only worry is that it'll be hard to tell the difference between Blitzwing and Starscream, but other than that, this movie is looking to be so goddamn AMAZING!

text: 11 years since the first movie. It took 11 years to make THE Transformers movie. If you are going to make better films of the franchise from now on, please move this movie away from the others. As a small restart, bringing with it a new team of people, directors who give their own vision of Transformers and not repeat the formulas. Travis Knight is a capable director, the fact of having directed stop-motion movies gives him an unparalleled visual capacity if we compare him with Bay or other directors. This Bumblebee is different, it is not the same as the other 5 previous films, it has a personality that he should not lose, because if he lose it, stop being that character with whom it is easy to smile in less than 3 minutes of trailer. Have this movie as a small reboot, with Peter Cullen back, but with everyone else involved in the previous ones out of the map, because in 11 years they were not able to do something this big, and a small restart is at the same time a big reboot. Do not ruin it by having the opportunity. Thanks Travis and everyone involved who thought to go beyond those who only went to the same place in 11 years. This looks beautiful.

text: Whilst I applaud the visual design in the recent Bay movies they were somewhat unfaithful to the original transformers. There where some comments in the bonus disc of the first movie from both the design team and Shia LaBeouf to the effect of "only 10 people on the internet care about what they looked like". I appreciate the idea of making Soundwave a tape player is weird and there was a need for change, but the visual design in this trailer shows they are now striking a balance between being faithful to the iconic designs I grew up with and a modern look. When I first seen the original movies I got excited at the prospect of a "real action" Transformers movie but it turned out to be an expensive advertising campaign. Watching this trailer, whilst thematically far from the original seems to give me more confidence...

text: So imma just go and eat some 10-year old crow right now...  I've kinda been an apologist for at least the _character designs_ of the first few Transformers films (the Bay-formers). A lotta folks didn't like the way they looked, said they were "too messy" or "piles of garbage." But I used to think they looked as good as they could ever hope to in live-action...  I was wrong. *DEAD* wrong. These designs are simply immaculate! Every one of the robots look distinct. Optimus, Shockwave, and Soundwave in particular made my jaw drop.  I'm still not _completely_ confident that the movie will be great, but at the very least, these designs are what they always should've been.

text: All right here we go, I hate being this guy, but I have a small issue with this trailer, and it is the fact that it seems like a trailer for two separate movies. Let me explain what I mean, it is the differing aesthetics within the trailer. The transformers on earth have the Bay-verse live action aesthetics, where as the ones on Cybertron have a G1/WFC design and they clash in my opinion.  Donâ€™t get me wrong I love the G1 fan service (and that is all it is) I really do, and I am looking forward to seeing more of â€œthisâ€ Cybertronâ€ on the big screen, which is way better than anything Bay gave us (meaning Cybertron wise), but like I said except for that message from Optimus, it looks like two separate movies are being advertised in the trailer. I donâ€™t know how many of you saw Digimon:The Movie from the year 2000, well in the US version what they did was combined three separate movies (that is how they were released in Japan ), so that the running time would be longer , but the three movies all had different art styles, designs and narrative. So they attempted to tie (not a pun) all of them together, while editing parts out, making changes, which just lead to a very confusion movieâ€¦..unless you loved Digimon enough and the fact that it was on the big screen forgave all of that, you might of left the theater sayingâ€¦â€¦â€WTFâ€.  Of course another example I could use, which might be a better one come to think of it isâ€¦â€¦.ROBOTECHâ€¦â€¦.and that is what this trailer is making me think what the Bumblebee Movie will be likeâ€¦â€¦â€¦it will be like watching ROBOTECH.  If Bumblebee, Dropkick, Shatter and Blitzwing had more of that G1 design then I would feel different, but they donâ€™t. It almost feels like they â€œaddedâ€ all this Cybertron stuff after the initial movie was done filming and edited.  Like I donâ€™t know if it is a spoiler, but Hasbro has made â€œnewâ€ figures for the Bumblebee movie-line of Bumblebee as the Classic Camaro he was at the beginning of the 2007 movie, and a lot of people have said that at the end of this film he will be scanning that carâ€¦..hence leading into that adventure.  I am just hoping this is not a way to make â€œG1ersâ€ happy or satisfied, while throwing away canon, design, and consistency of the movie itself.  It reminds me of that game from a few years ago â€œRise of the Dark Sparkâ€, where the WFC universe crossed over with the live action universe, and at times the differing designs got jarring and that was for just a game.  Alsoâ€¦â€¦if this is a prequel, then they all should look like their protoforms as seen in the 2007 movieâ€¦..but you know what let us kick Mister OCD out the doorâ€¦..but let us get Mister Nitpicker the realist in hereâ€¦â€¦ Why do they have EARTH Vehicle/and or Devices parts on their Cybertronian bodies?  Fine the first G1 episode did that (among others), but come on, no excuse will make this acceptable.  Again I love the scene with Cybertron, it just does not look like it fits into the rest of the movie, but that does not mean I am not going to love this G1 fan service, because I definitely willâ€¦..but at what cost. #BUMBLEBEEMOVIE #TRANSFORMERS

text: The G1 designs are absolutely fantastic. But to be fair, some of the transformers here do have influences from the Bayformer franchise such as Bumblebee and Thundercracker. Which is pretty cool since that means to an extent, Bay and Spielberg did set a certain standard to how Transformers should look and feel in live action. The huge difference was that he tried to make it more realistic and more adult orientated, which is probably why most transformers in that franchise was redesigned to a ridiculous degree in which many donâ€™t even resemble their original G1 look.  Imho it really started to go downhill from T4 as the transformers were made to look less robotic and more humanoid which completely defeats the purpose of setting them apart as *alien robots* in the first place. I guess the reason for that drastic change was to sell new toys smh.  EDIT: Keep in mind, Iâ€™m only referring to the *design* of the transformers from the films. The second movie was garbage but it still used the same aesthetic from the first one. DOTM used it too but AOE and TLN literally looked like as if they were pieces of wet tissue twisted together in contrast to the more complete robotic look from the first three films.

text: One of my best friend was twice my age and drove a Blue VW Beetle and passed away 6 years ago now. He was 70 years old when he died and I'm 32 now almost 33. I used to work with him traveling all around the city in his Blue Beetle telling me stories, cracking jokes, meditating. That Beetle is still around and everytime I see it I think of him smoking his unfilter smokes and talking about life. I miss him very much. Seening this trailer and that old guy talking to Charlie  remind me of him. He was somewhat sarcastic but he was a very likable guy, like that old man. I almost cry in this trailer. Thank you for this.

text: Okay, so I know G1 transformers are the best but stop criticising Mitchell Bay for that Bayformers saga. I admit that transformers 3 was not good at all and 4 was sh!t but transformers 5 was GOOD (at least the ending was). But yeah this is *TRANSFORMERS DONE RIGHT*  Edit: @VPT2 and @Larry The Mighty Eagle yeah I know Tf5 wasn't that good but the ending was *(in my point of view)* very good. The decepticons did get one shot killed etc. but Sir Edmund and Cogman were amazing characters. The car chase scenes in the McLaren and also the one with Bee were good. The speech by Optimus, Cade taking out that sword to save Optimus, these were all good scenes.  I also love the G1 Transformers *(of course)* but they look a bit too cartoonish compared to the BayFormers.

text: This looks pathetic. How many times must the developers fail before they learn copy/pasting an old look just doesn't work. People in the comments are blinded by nostalgia. You're not going to get your childhood back. It may have a greater resemblance to the G1 show than the Michael Bay movies, but that is simply cosmetic. The Transformers was cool because you had a giant roster of Autobots and Decepticons fighting each other. Having just one Transformer isn't going to be fun. Bumblebee was never even that important of a character anyway before the Bay films. He was pretty small and weak.  The reason I think the Michael Bay films are good Transformers films in spite of whatever weak writing may be there is because they capture the feel of the G1 show, without the look. The special effects are phenomenal, and in a Transformers film that really is most of what counts. The rest of the appeal comes from the way the Transformers talk. They use common Earth expressions but replace our words with words used for automobiles or machinery. All you need is good animation, good action, and good dialogue. The Bay films deliver on that admirably.  This trailer looks like a weird attempt at merging the G1 animation style, which was excellent in its day and original medium, with the CGI of the Bay films, and it just doesn't look very impressive on the big screen.

text: This looks like it was originally going to be a remake, and/or sequel to The Iron Giant, but at the last minute before production, they decided to make it part of the Transformers universe by replacing all of the characters to ones in the Transformers universe, while keeping most of the original script with changes both minor, and major. And before anyone disproves my theory, hear me out on all of the similarities . 1. Giant robot lands on Earth and is unfamiliar with the place  2. There is a character that teaches said robot the ways of the humans  3. There is some sort of government official that is trying to get rid of it.  It is also implied in The Iron Giant Signature Edition that the robots were in a war that ended up in the destruction of a planet, and in this movie, there is a war happening between Transformers that could end up destroying the planet they came from. Iâ€™m not saying that it will be a bad movie, I just think that companies should stop slapping properties on top of other properties. I could be wrong, and if Iâ€™m wrong, you can reply.

text: I'm an 80's kid.  Yeah I get Bumblee.  He was always the heart of the autobots.  The quiet fan favorite if you will.  BUT it's 2018 now.  Aren't the transformers irrelevant now?  The cartoon died decades ago.  And even when the revamped it, it didn't last long.  This movie appeals to kids and young teens.  But the ones who would appreciate like me are 40+ and have packed up our toys a long time ago.  I'm not going to rush out to see this.  If I was still 13 I'd be there in a heart beat.  But they need to sell this movie to a generation who probably doesn't even remember George Bush much less GI JOE or Gummie Bears or Smurfs or Thundercats or Voltron or Transformers.

text: I was very impressed by the Bumblebee Teaser Trailer, but this trailer is just so... not good. Its just a big nothing. When you put those stupid big "epic" drum buildup beats without any music or other audio to accompany it, it just sounds incredibly stupid, and that's exactly what happened in this trailer. Might I also say the most of the dialogue feels bad/ out of place/ given with the wrong delivery.  The little music that is in the trailer also sounds incredibly stupid and basic. Although, I'm very impressed by the CGI, and you can clearly tell Michael Bay isn't directing this, but after seeing this trailer, my expectations have dropped all the way back down from the high hopes I had after watching the teaser. I'm not sure now whether this movie will be surprisingly good, or just another bad movie about transformers.

text: I watched the new bumblebee trailer. I just have one issue. The g1 designs in the scenes from cybertron. They are too much like the g1 version. To much like they came out of the war for cybertron video game. Itâ€™s not realistic. The one good thing I liked the most about when bay was in charge was the designs. They were still true to the characters to where u knew who they were. But they were in a far more realistic light and not so blocky. They were a perfect representation of an alien tech based humanoid life form. The one thing that threw me off the most was shockwave and soundwave. To much like g1.  This is what I was afraid of when they started to do things write. Over correcting. Like now we get a good story with otherwise less awesome designs. Iâ€™m not bashing fans of the old movie from the 80s. Heck the first tf series I ever completed watching growing up was armada and that style was a lot like the old one in terms of blockiness. But u canâ€™t go that literal with a realistic interpretation. They need to be more like if a living creature with an fully functional body structure was made of metal. Plus the armor and vehicle modes would hardly at all resemble human vehicles if they havenâ€™t come here yet. They would be rather alien like they were shown in previous films.

text: Sorry to spam this trailer but I can't stop watching it, it gives me chills down my spine.  How is it that Paramount just now FINALLY gave us G1 Transformers?  Those of us who grew up with them were screaming about the designs of the Bayformers during every film (Optimus and Bumblebee are the only two they got close to being right).  We bought the G1 games, the 'retro' merchandise, flocked to any G1 fan film... ANYTHING G1... yet, nobody would listen.  FINALLY they righted the wrong of what Bay did to the Transformers that we loved.  These guys are now colorful, recognizable... not just twisted grey metal where you have no idea who is who.  Thanks for getting this right.

text: TAKE MY MONEY! This is how a Transformers movie should be. G1 and full of kind, brave characters full of heart and soul. Now give me this, but as a TV series! Live action, with these graphics. also keep it clean. A movie for adults doesn't have to be filthy. Rediscover the lost art of story telling.  I want to see cybertron before the war and all the politics that lead up to it. No humans. WORLD BUILDING.  Show me what a cybertronian home looks like, show me city streets, show me Megatron and Optimus before they were enemies. Show me starscream the winglord of Vos,  show me Mirage the towerling. Show me Jazz the music lover and his club. Prowl the cop. Show me thundercracker and skywarp and explain just what a trine is.  Show me cybertronian religion. I want to see cybertronian culture,  I want to see temples to Primus and see the giant spark of Primus himself. Also I want to see Megatron as an intelligent and highly thoughtful and purposeful character who chooses his path for legitimate reasons. Make me love this guy and sympathize with him and his choices. Do the same for Prime too. Ultimate goal, you will have fans firmly divided into factions as to who they support because both sides just have darn good arguments and reasons for doing what they do. No more one dimensional characters.

text: Thank Primus, Bay is less involved now.  The values and attitudes of the characters in the Bay films were so hateful and negative. People were petty and spiteful and egocentric. Nobody was ever nice to each other. And that wasn't done to make the audience think critically and reflect on their values. Bumblebee actually looks like characters are going to be expressing positive sentiments towards one another.  I have not seen either of Christina Hodson's other films, but from the trailer Bumblebee seems to have more humanity than all the Bay films put together.  Travis Knight has been the lead animator on some really wonderful animated films, and directed / animated Kubo.  These are family movies which I believe usually feature a moral, and all appear to have solid storytelling.  I have faith that Christina and Travis can make a better, more compassionate story than the lingerie / milk commercial guy did.  Transformers should have been for kids. The toys are meant for kids. Why did they let it become a homophobic, misogynistic (it also denigrates men too, not just women), commercial mess?  Do they want 8 year olds to go to the store and buy an Optimus figure, then go get some Bud light, and then join the army? I would not let a child watch the other transformers movies.  Bumblebee might actually be ok.

text: Overall it was a good film. Well made, excellent CGI and fight scenes. And a nice simplicity to its story.  But.....  It is a part of the current trend of turning boys into girls and girls into boys. I guess it's a different meaning of the word.  Transformers was originally a boys cartoon, full of violence and tribal allegiance. And this movie has all of that. But it's confusing gender roles by having the girl as the mechanic and the boy with the embarrassing range of hair products. While slamming the "normal kids", the friends who are masculine males and the feminine females. ie: 95% of the population.  Then they try to sell us on the idea that an 18 year metal loving, mechanic chick is a perfect christian when it comes to dating.  And the final song as the credits role was fluffy bunny stuff.  Come on Hollywood. How about making one for the normal people for a change.  But the action was first rate. And if you're into that other stuff and 5+ years old go see it.

text: Make a movie about real life that real people will find relatable and useful. You can make a lot of those with a lower budget because you won't need any computer graphics. That will save you a lot of money. That could eventually lower movie ticket prices. Imagine...people going to theaters again to see movies that they can afford and that they can relate to. Sounds crazy, but just think about it. Movies for everyday people in everyday situations. The movie will present one variation and that will allow people to compare/contrast their own lives to the movie/story in front of them. What iffff people found this useful and went to movies regularly to help them navigate various social situations and life events?? Egads, re-discover the purpose of story telling. Unless...................the whole point all along has been to displace, stun, and disorient viewers with over-worked fantasy images in order to make them more susceptible to the propaganda and advertisements. Well...only you the elite movie business can say where you went off track from story telling and why. Only you or your replacement industry will be able to get humans back on track with real story telling. Fantasy films are ok but not the way Hollywood has been doing them for over a decade or two. Ah well, you know where to contact me if you need real feedback on movies.

text: Uhhhhh... I am really confused by the overwhelmingly positive response that this movie has gotten. I saw it with my girlfriend the other day and it was by no means terrible, but was it great? In my opinion not really. Correct me if I am wrong, but doesn't one of the very first scenes in the movie involve a girl listening to music with her headphones, that are plugged into... wait for it... the sink? that she just used to brush her teeth?  I mean you literally see this same girl get hit by a missile in a dumpster and she just walks out of it like nothing even happened? The army guys that are obsessed with destroying everything they find? The government's weird fetish for dismantling a transformer for scrap parts? These are just some of the many scenes that took me out of the immersion and made me question if anything even makes sense or not. No disrespect to anyone who genuinely thought this was a great movie, but the more I think about it, the more I wonder if we even saw the same movie.  I got 6/10 vibes here, maybe even a 7 for some of the better moments, and some cool 80s references, but anything higher than that... mmm, not from me, sorry.

text: Well I didn't like how they handled Charlie's family half the time and the nerd dude should've been more than a 1 dimensional character but besides some of the cliched screenplay I have to say it was a nice movie and I liked Charlie as a protagonist.  The only Transformers movie I liked from the Bay films was the first one and just a little bit from the third film.  This one easily tops them though.  If you liked films like the Iron Giant you'll get a similar vibe from this one.  If they make a sequel I hope they don't cheese the script as much, Bay's films had a glaring issue in that they often got easily distracted by pointless toilet humor.

text: Before time itself, there was a being called 'The One' who represented order and chaos in harmony. 'The One' wanted to explore more of the universe and thus split into two beings, Unicron and Primus. Unicron representing chaos, and Primus representing order. Primus found out that Unircon was destroying (eating) planets and thus made the 'Thirteen Primes' (not going to name them all) to help him destroy unicron. After unicrons defeat, his body drifted into space and eventually formed the earth's core. Primus then became one with the core cypertron where he gives his life to future transformers trough the Alspark in the 'Well Of All Sparks'. A bit of conflict started between 'The Thirteen Primes' and Liege Maximo manipulated Megatronus into killing Solus Prime. Her body unexpectedly melted into the core of cypertron wich formed the 'Well Of All Sparks'. Onyx Prime, Micronus Prime, and the Thirteen Prime Willingly enter the Well Of All Sparks' and sacrifice their lives in order to jump-start its creative processes, with the intent of creating a new race to inhabit  cybertron. Meanwhile, Quintus Prime travels into deep space with an Emberstone to create a race that would ally future cybertronian civlizations and thus creates the Quintessons. The 'Thirteenth Prime' comes out of the 'Well Of All Sparks' reincarnated as Orion Pax who as we know becomes Optimus Prime. Cut a long story short the Quintessons made the transformers their slaves and took over cybertron by creating their own goverment and laws. The transformers then rebel against the Quintessons and force them off the planet. The transformers then lived in peace. Then overtime some transformers believed that chaos was the best way to live, whilst others thought that order was the best way to live(Autobots and Decepticons). text: If you haven't watched this movie yet, go see it right NOW. I kid you not when I say that Bumblebee is by far the best movie of 2018. This is not some soulless cash grab like so many blockbuster movies seem to be these days. Instead of mindless action scenes and forgettable jokes, this movie has genuinely emotional moments, well developed characters, terrifying villains, and a lot of heart. If any action movie deserves an Oscar, it's not Infinity War or Into the Spider Verse but this simple but emotional story about a girl and her best friend who belong together but fate would not have it be that way.

None of the bots seemed humanlike as it was in the last Bayformer movies, but they had their own â€œimageâ€. In this movie transformers seemed nerfed and pretty childish. However i feel fucking riped off when it comes to quality of the movie itself compared to the previous ones. The CGI outside the focus of Bumblebee was dogshit. The Timeline doesnt match the the history presented in the previous ones either. Now Michael Bay started something epic, in the same line Blizzard produces their Cinematics for their World of Warcraft branch. u expect top notch CGI and quality. Bumblebee did not deliver in that mather.  the story of Charlie and Bee was alright, the story outside of that was non existing. If they combine both aspects of the Previous Movies with a bigger story line, and not cut the budget on CGI quality. this can be a perfect re-start for the  franchise. but it can also end in a fat flop if they continue with this example

text: Bumblebee was my first crush ever. I was six years old. Always thought I was strange for crushing on a cartoon robot but now over thirty years later it seems maybe other people get it too? XD  Or maybe not and I'm just strange. Anyway, how come he can't talk like he could in the original cartoon? Why did they change his model so much? Also, I noticed that there are a lot of positive comments about how wonderful this movie is-- and maybe it is, I've not seen it yet (and I haven't seen any of the other CGI movies)-- but I can't help feeling like this will just be very predictable?  Something along the lines of Short Circuit or ET, that tugs at your heartstrings because "the lovable creature is being targeted by authorities but he's your special frieeeeeend... and he will save you and sacrifice for you and the true meaning of friendship and it's so sad when the authorities temporarily catch him and do mean things to him but in the end he is saved and everyone cries out of happiness and he leaves to go to his home but he will never forget youuuuu" *last shot in the film is the human friend looking out into the distance while smiling and shedding a tear and leaning their head against the shoulder of their beloved (because the whole adventure had brought them together)

text: Perhaps the director can tell me, what exactly they know about cars that thought her expertise would be shown by knowing what size of wrench they needed (and how someone who is supposed to be an old mechanic, wouldn't be able to tell at a glance. One of the first skills you pick up). But more importantly, what she was doing to the transmission/driveshaft that would have affected whether or not the car started? (The answer is nothing because that's not how a '60s car works)  If you don't want to look like fools, and you want her to look good, have the engine on a stand (gutted). Then have her fiddling with cleaning something (like the carb or fuel pump), expertise will be assumed by the work already done not by the work being done. ...Which was obviously nothing since she wasn't even working in the engine bay.  Why was she having so much trouble? Spark issue: coil, plugs, or distributor. Fuel/air: Carb, fuel pump, or regulator. Doesn't crank: starter/battery... possibly ignition (if there is no power to the acc.). Those are basically the only things on an engine of that age. If it sparks and gets fuel but only sputters, then test compression or adjust the carb. There are so few wires, any wiring issue should be easily visible....  Just, why? You could've asked some random parts clerk and they would've given you better direction.

text: So I saw the movie and it's about time we got a good Transformers film. However, John Cena may be a good actor as a wrestler but he doesn't translate well to film. The parents acting wasn't good either.  Everything with them felt forced. But the actress  Hailee Steinfeld was amazing, and she is amazing in anything she plays in. The story was well done and the 80's work not just because it's popular again, but because it's the right era for this film. Other than Bumble Bee in robot form, the other Autobots actually look like what they are suppose to. Soundwave also looks like how he should (my favorite decepticon). Christina Hodson wrote this film and she delivers on providing a really good story with allot of fun and emotion mixed in. I'd really love to have this movie on Blu-ray. And again, it's about time we got a good Transformers movie. I highly suggest this film to anyone, even if you don't care for sci-fi. It's a clean and fun movie for the whole family.

text: Finally a Transformers movie made by a true filmmaker and the franchise may finally ignite the series. The issue has always been Michael Bay's style of humour and lack of direction for the characters. Knight on the other hand course corrects and provides a heartfelt connection to the series. The first 10 minutes are some of the most impressive action scenes of the series, relentless. It is a shame that audiences have neglected this, most likely due to the very poor Last Knight storyline. They have a chance to ignore the other movies in the franchise now and it is a good idea, the mythology of the characters was essentially destroyed by a director with little or no care for the franchise. I hope Knight returns in some form and Bay is sidelined for the future, think Snyder for the DC universe. This is a funny and at times heartfelt story, that services the fans and new fans at the same time. Great action and without the dumb jokes that plague the Transformers central series. Watch online free HD Movies https://gomovies.im/movies/bumblebee/

text: I may be asking for a lot here, but if you could just turn that first 3 minutes into an entire full-length G1-centric movie in which no characters die and also includes Frank Welker's Megatron, you will have finally succeeded in making THE Transformers Movie that I've been dying to see.  Seriously, a friend showed the clip to me & I was literally ready, ON THE SPOT, to jump in the car & fly over to AMC Citywalk so I could catch the next showing.  Luckily they stopped me & told me that THAT was the ONLY EPIC part of the entire movie. The rest was good, they said, sure... but not First 3 Minutes EPIC.  Still waiting for EPIC. No teases. No carrot dangling. No human drama interfering & completely taking over the A & B Plots while the Giant Transforming Robots at War that I WANT to see are shoved into a back seat C Plot or killed off 30 seconds after they're introduced.  I just want Transformers, y'all. Just like those first 2 seasons gave us in the 80's. Fun, thrilling stories about awesome Transforming robots that are forced to interact in & around our world but are not ultimately overshadowed nor hindered by the fact. They do so in secret. Without our knowledge. Hence... the whole Transforming thing. But should a human or two absolutely HAVE to be around, they're the sidekicks, or occasional background noise. NOT the stars.  Anyways, Rant/Praise Over  That First 3 Minutes just showed me that you DO KNOW HOW & absolutely CAN MAKE a FOR REALZ LEGIT Transformers Movie! text: I just watched it and i'll give it a 3/10 and 2 points come the fact it was a part of transformers and the other 1 was because it was simple to follow.   This movie was clearly written by a self-centered woman whose goals were to pander to the audience with non-stop cliches while depicting an actress that is struggling with nothing more than her own feelings about herself.  I have never seen a "basic" main character be depicted as shallow and narrow minded in a movie ever before.  1) She is full of herself the whole movie.  2) She was a depressing drag 90% of the time.  3) Though the movie was called Bumblebee, it was really about a shallow girl who only cared about herself.  4) She ignores everyone around her the whole movie, no humility what-so-ever.  The movie should have been called, Girl Kidnaps Bumblebee.  The movie could have been 30 minutes shorter if they would have left out the cheesy cliches.  The writer made Bubblebee very week and gave him puppy dog eyes for crying out loud.  The CGI was the worst I have ever seen in the last 10 years.   And by the way, they should never be allowed to make another Transformers Film without Michael Bay directing it.  Period.

text: Ok, so this movie is supposed to be about BumbleBee first coming to Earth and basically his origin story. In the timeline, BumbleBee comes to Earth in 1974 I think. But in Transformers 5, we are shown that the Transformers have long been on Earth before 1974. BumbleBee helped the allies win in World War 2. Optimus Prime helped George Washington in the American Revolution. The Guardian Knights helped the English beat the enemies. So this basically just messed up the entire timeline because, in the end, we see that BumbleBee transforms into a Camaro using his scanning thingy. That Camaro was the same 1974 Camaro we first see the car BumbleBee appears as in the first 2 (I think its 2) Transformers movies. So obviously this movie was supposed to lead up to the rest of the Transformers movies. That still doesn't add up because like I said earlier, Bumblebee and the transformers have already been at Earth before 1974.  Also! Why in Transformers 1 to 5, would the military attack the Autobots if Bumblebee literally saved Earth all by himself. Also, also! Why would they even attack BumbleBee in the first place if he helped the allies beat the Nazis!

text: I don't know why hasbro confirmed this is a reboot, and I don't know why people are saying this is a reboot, because this is a prequel and spin off. How this is a spin off is that it focuses on bee. How this is a prequel is that it still has bee's design from the 5 films, the same crew from the 5 michael bay films worked on this(yes even michael bay himself but he only produced)(SPOILERS for my comment so avoid it if you haven't seen the film yet.) It showed that bee used to have a name B 127 and how he got the name bumblebee, it showed how he lost his voice in war and speaks through radio with music and with different voices, bee was the only autobot on earth until the autobots came just like in the first film l, seymor simmons from the films is in this but younger, sector 7's in this just like in the first 3 films, not only all those, but this is also the first transformers film to not have Megatron since the first film revealed that he was frozen for decades(FUN FACT:he was supposed to appear in this, but was taken out, because travis knight wanted it to keep continuity with the michael bay films). Edit:one more thing the teaser used bernie mac's audio from the first film and the teaser also said "every hero has a beginning".

text: Just way better as a character driven story than the other ones, which were frankly pretty toxic. Small fix I would like to suggest to fix a 2-3 minor plot weaknesses: * It was a bit weak that the decepticons did not make sure Bumblebee was dead after so dramatically cutting in half that other autobot around Saturn. * The green powercell thing is not explained, or that there is only one etc. * When the girl (Charlie) overcame her fears and dived into the water at the end, there was nothing specific at stake. There wasn't something she actually could expect to do.  My fix is that: * The decepticons _DO_ dramatically kill Bumblebee. They yank out his heart. This will be the unexplained green powercell they are using to power their signal. * Charlie has some basic knowledge of BB's electrical system from wiring in that radio. Her goal with shooting him with those electric guns is to charge his capacitors. Capacitors give him the ability for a few minutes of activity only. She could also hook his power to a truck and drive him to the final battle, but that is a detail. * At the end he has exerted all his power and this is why he sinks to the bottom unmoving. * When she dives into the water, the point is to restore his heart to him.
